11 recodified by subsection (c) of this section, reads as rewritten:
12 "Part 4. North Carolina Center for Missing Persons.
13 "§ 143B-1760. North Carolina Center for Missing Persons established.
14 There is established within the Department of Public Safety State Highway Patrol the North
15 Carolina Center for Missing Persons, which shall be organized and staffed in accordance with
16 applicable laws. The purpose of the Center is to serve as a central repository for information
17 regarding missing persons and missing children, with special emphasis on missing children. The
18 Center may utilize the Federal Bureau of Investigation/National Crime Information Center's
19 missing person computerized file (hereinafter referred to as FBI/NCIC) through the use of the
20 Police Information Network in the North Carolina Department of Justice.
21 …
22 "§ 143B-1762. Control of the Center.
23 The Center is under the direction of the Secretary of the Department of Public Safety
24 Commander of the State Highway Patrol and may be organized and structured in a manner as the
25 Secretary deems appropriate to ensure that the objectives of the Center are achieved. The
26 Secretary Commander may employ those Center personnel as the General Assembly may
27 authorize and provide funding for.
28 "§ 143B-1763. Secretary Commander to adopt rules.
29 The Secretary Commander of the State Highway Patrol shall adopt rules prescribing all of
30 the following:
31 (1) Procedures for accepting and disseminating information maintained at the
32 Center.
33 (2) The confidentiality of the data and information, including the missing person
34 report, maintained by the Center.
35 (3) The proper disposition of all obsolete data, including the missing person
36 report; provided, data for an individual who has reached the age of 18 and
37 remains missing must be preserved.
38 (4) Procedures allowing a communication link with the Police Information
39 Network and the FBI/NCIC's missing person file to ensure compliance with
40 FBI/NCIC policies.
41 (5) Forms, including but not limited to a missing person report, considered
42 necessary for the efficient and proper operation of the Center.
43 …
44 "§ 143B-1765. Dissemination of missing persons data by law-enforcement agencies.
